Summary

On December 27, 2023, at 11:22 AM UTC, the SOC team received an alert titled “SOC250 – APT35 HyperScrape Data Exfiltration Tool Detected.” The alert was triggered when a suspicious executable named "EmailDownloader.exe"—linked to the APT35 (Charming Kitten) Hyperscrape tool —was executed on host Arthur with IP 172.16.17.72.

Earlier at 11:17 AM UTC, user Arthur successfully logged in via RDP (Logon Type 10) from an external IP 173.209.51.54, indicating potential unauthorized remote access. Shortly after, the malicious file EmailDownloader.exe was executed from the path `C:\Users\LetsDefend\Downloads\EmailDownloader.exe`. The file’s hash cd2ba296828660ecd07a36e8931b851dda0802069ed926b3161745aae9aa6daa was identified as malicious on VirusTotal.

At 11:21 AM UTC, Microsoft Exchange logs showed multiple email downloads from Arthur’s mailbox (`Operation: Download`, `FolderPath: \Mails\Inbox`), consistent with Hyperscrape email extraction activity. Immediately after the download, the infected host established an outbound HTTP connection to 136.243.108.14, an IP reported as malicious for email exfiltration.

An OSINT check confirmed that both the file hash and the external IPs (173.209.51.54 and 136.243.108.14) were associated with malicious activity.

I have disconnected the host from the network, revoked all active sessions for user Arthur, and initiated containment procedures pending further remediation.


